Good effort, BUT it isn't in "PURE CD QUALITY EXPERIENCE!?!?!?!?!?" as you claim.
Firstly: It's in MP3, so it will always be funamentally different, to be CD quality needs FLAC, APE or Wav.
Secondly: You have chosen the very worst of the 3 MP3 formats, Joint Stereo, that actually isn't even proper stereo at all. Joint Stereo shares certain bits between high frequency left and right channels, it is OK for low bitrates only and cuts high frequencies and stereo separation.
Even using "Stereo" is not that good, The only way to get the very best out of MP3 is to use Dual Channel, or Dual Stereo, then you DO get 2 separate left and right channels, and the best sound possible with an MP3.
